While an experimental vaccine appears to be able to reduce Ebola mortality, there are currently no drugs that have been proven to be clearly suitable for the treatment of existing infections.
An antibody cocktail, ZMapp, initially showed promise, but formal studies showed that it, in terms of preventing deaths, had fewer benefits than hoped for.
In the PALM study, ZMapp was used as a control, i.e. the scientists used it as a baseline and compared the three other treatments with it.
USA Gymnastics supports the letter from the United States Olympic Committee and accepts it as an absolute necessity that the Olympic family works to create a safe environment for all of our athletes.
We agree with the USOC’s statement that the best interests of our athletes and clubs and their sport are served by moving forward with meaningful changes within our organization, rather than pursuing decertification.
USA Gymnastics supports an independent investigation that could bring to light how abuse on the scale described so bravely by the survivors of Larry Nassar could have gone undetected for so long, and welcomes all necessary and appropriate changes.
USA Gymnastics and the USOC share the same goal - to make gymnastics and other sports as safe as possible for athletes so they can follow their dreams in a safe, positive and self-determined environment.
During the 1960s, Brzezinski served as an advisor to John F. Kennedy and later to the administration of Lyndon B. Johnson.
During the 1976 elections, he advised Carter on foreign policy and then served from 1977 to 1981 as national security advisor (NSA) in succession to Henry Kissinger.
As national security advisor, he assisted Carter in the diplomatic handling of world affairs such as the Camp David Accords of 1978, the normalization of relations between the United States and China in the late 1970s, the Iranian Revolution, which led to the Iran hostage crisis of 1979, and the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in 1979.
